Indonesia Stocks: Astra Agro Lestari, Bukopin, Bumi Resources

-- B y   B e r n i   M o e s t a f a
-- 
2011-04-04T09:35:13Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-04/indonesia-stocks-bakrie-sumatera-bank-bukopin-london-sumatra.html
Shares of the following companies
had unusual moves in Indonesian trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses, and prices are as of the 4 p.m. Jakarta-time close.  The  Jakarta Composite index (JCI)  fell 7.44 points, or 0.2
percent, to 3,700.05, the first decline in four days.  Palm oil producers: PT Astra Agro Lestari (AALI IJ), the
nation’s biggest listed plantation company by market value, fell
1.8 percent to 22,500 rupiah. PT Perusahaan Perkebunan London
Sumatra  Indonesia  (LSIP IJ), the second-largest, retreated 1.1
percent to 2,325 rupiah and PT BW Plantation (BWPT IJ) fell 1.7
percent to 1,170 rupiah.  Southeast Asia ’s plantation industry was cut to
“underweight” from “market weight” at UOB-Kay Hian Holdings
Ltd. because palm oil prices are expected to peak in the first
half of 2011 and weaken in the second half, according to a
report.  PT Bank Bukopin (BBKP IJ), the bank that is owned by
cooperatives, rose 2.9 percent to 700 rupiah, the highest close
since Oct. 26. Bukopin may sell as much as 1 trillion rupiah
($115 million) of subordinated debt in the first half of this
year to boost capital, Finance Director Tri Joko Prihanto said
in Jakarta today.  PT Bumi Resources (BUMI IJ),  Asia ’s biggest exporter of
power-station coal, declined 2.3 percent to 3,250 rupiah, the
sharpest drop since Feb. 22. Power-station coal  prices  at
 Australia ’s Newcastle port, an Asian benchmark, fell 2.2 percent
to $121.13 a metric ton in the week ended April 1, according to
the  globalCOAL NEWC Index .  To contact the reporter on this story:
Berni Moestafa in Jakarta at 
 bmoestafa@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
